1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Rb1 a5 7. a3 Nf6 8. Nf3 O-O
9. O-O h6 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 Be6 12. b5 Ne7 13. Bb2 Nd7 14. Nd2 c6 15. Ra1
Qc7 16. Qc2 Nf5 17. Rfc1 Nf6 18. Qd1 Qd7 {We have a typical English opening
middlegame. Black seems to be well regrouped and even has some space advantage
in the center, but his f5-knight is not very effectively placed. At the same
time, White's minor pieces are perfectly coordinated, making Ulf's decision to
transpose to an ending after a long series of major piece exchanges look
logical.} 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Ra1 Qc8 (20... Rb8 21. Ra7 $16) 21. Rxa8 Qxa8 22.
Qa4 $1 {The most effective way of offering the queen exchange as it activates
both queenside pieces.} Qxa4 23. Nxa4 {Black has serious problems to keep his
structure intact, as White attacks with all his pieces, while some of Black's
are mere spectators.} Bd7 {Finding the lesser evil is not simple.} ({If} 23...
Ne7 24. bxc6 Nxc6 (24... bxc6 25. c5 $16 {leaves Black's structure chronically
weak.}) 25. Nb6 Bf8 26. Nb1 $5 {Heading for d5 or b5.} Be7 27. Nc3 Bd8 28. Nbd5
$16 {Black has a very difficult ending due to his weaknesses on b7 and d6.}) (
23... cxb5 24. cxb5 Bd7 {does not bring the desired relief:} 25. Nc3 Nd4 (25...
b6 26. Nc4 Nd4 27. Nxb6 Be8 28. Nc8 $16 {wins the d6-pawn.}) 26. Nc4 Bf8 ({
With hindsight, Black may consider} 26... Ne8 {, keeping e5 well defended. But
this weakens the control of the light squares, allowing} 27. b6 Bc6 28. Nd5 {
followed by Na5 with a quick win due to the weakness of the b7-pawn.}) 27. Bxb7
(27. b6 {remains very strong but less effective than in the line above.} Bc6
28. Bxc6 Nxc6 29. Nb5 Ne8 30. e4 $16 {with a clear White advantage but no
concrete achievements yet.}) 27... Nxb5 28. f4 $16 {White will soon win a
pawn on e5.}) 24. Nb6 Be8 25. bxc6 Bxc6 {Black tries to use his bishop for
keeping his structure compact, but this just loses the b7-pawn.} ({True,} 25...
bxc6 {runs into the familiar} 26. c5 $16) 26. Nb3 $1 {There is no adequate
defence against Na5 followed by Nxb7, winning a pawn and keeping the better
structure. The fluence of White's minor piece play is simply impressive.} e4 {
For some reasons engines agree that this is Black's best chance, but I see it
more like a desperate gesture.} 27. Bxf6 Bxf6 28. Bxe4 Nd4 $2 ({
Underestimating Ulf's knight's vivacity. Relatively better was} 28... Bxe4 29.
dxe4 Nd4 30. Nxd4 Bxd4 31. Nd5 {even though White's win would remain beyond
doubt.}) 29. Bxc6 bxc6 30. Nxd4 Bxd4 31. Nc8 $1 {Suddenly, Black cannot defend
his pawns which just seemed to have joined in a compact tandem again.} Bc5 32.
Ne7+ 1-0

