1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. e3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8.
O-O d6 9. b3 d5 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bb2 Qa5 12. Qe1 Rd8 13. Rc1 Ba6 {Black has a
normal position but his next move placed the bishop on an unfortunate square.
In some cases cxd5 creates some tactical possibilities as the bishop will be
hanging and dxc4 might just place the pawn under a pin. But for all these
White needs to exchange the queens.} 14. Na4 $1 Qxe1 15. Rfxe1 {What is even
worse, the threat Nc5 is quite unpleasant now.} dxc4 (15... Nd7 {is likely to
run into the aforementioned trick:} 16. Ba3 ({It is probably better to keep
the bishops on the board as after} 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. cxd5 Bxe2 18. dxc6 Bb5 19.
cxd7 Bxa4 20. bxa4 Rxd7 {Black should be able to defend in the ensuing rook
ending.}) 16... Bf6 17. cxd5 $1 Bxe2 18. dxc6 Bb5 19. cxd7 Rxd7 ({With bishops
on the board} 19... Bxa4 20. bxa4 Rxd7 21. Red1 Rad8 22. Rxd7 Rxd7 23. Bb4 {
does not guarantee anything, as the a7-pawn is likely to become a target after
a2-a3, a4-a5 followed by the rook activation.}) 20. Red1 $16) (15... Ne4 {is
solid, but leaves Black with problems finding a good square for his bishop
after} 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. f3 Nf6 18. Nc5 Bc8 19. Red1 e5 20. g4 $5 $16 {
followed by a slow queenside attack starting with b3-b4.}) 16. Nc5 $1 {An
important intermediate move, based on some tactical finesses.} ({If} 16. Bxc4
Bxc4 (16... Bb5 {is also good.}) 17. Rxc4 Rd2 18. Rxc6 Rad8 {followed by ...
Ne4 with active play for the pawn.}) 16... c3 {This solves Black's problems
regarding his passive and hanging bishop, but the forced simplifications will
lead to a very unpleasant ending.} (16... Bb5 {does not work anymore as} 17.
bxc4 $18 {wins the bishop.}) (16... Bc8 17. Bxc4 {offers White a large
advantage due to his better development and the weakness on c6. Unfortunately
for Black, the counterplay based on} Rd2 {fails painfully after} 18. Bc3 Rxa2
19. b4 Ra3 20. Bb2 {, trapping the rook.}) 17. Bxc3 Bxe2 18. Rxe2 Rd5 19. Bxf6
Bxf6 20. Rec2 $16 {Ulf had this structure in many games, usually arising from
the symmetrical English/Semi-Tarrasch openings. His technique in exploiting
the queenside weaknesses yielded him excellent results even in those games
where Black had positional compensation for the shattered structure.  But in
this concrete position, White has a big advantage as the bishop can do little
for the defense of the c6-pawn or for generating counterplay.} Rad8 {Now and a
few moves later Black is not paying attention to the weak pawn, trying to get
counterplay along the open file.} (20... Rc8 {was more solid, but would not
spare Black from his problems.} 21. g3 Kg7 22. Ne4 Ra5 23. Rd2 $16 {White
controls the position and can strengthen his pressure with Rc4 followed by the
advance of the kingside pawns.}) 21. g3 h5 22. Kg2 Kg7 23. Ne4 {The start of a
curious knight maneuver which, as the reader already knows from the previous
article, is quite typical for Andersson.} Ra5 24. Nc5 Rb8 $2 {This simply
loses the pawn. Black must have overlooked the next move.} ({It was essential
to keep the pressure on a2 with} 24... Ra3 {, when White could play} 25. Re2 {
, preparing Rc4.} Be5 26. Na4 Rc8 27. Rc4 Bd6 28. f4 $16 {and Black will soon
be suffocated.}) 25. Na4 $1 {The a2-pawn is safe and the c6 pawn is doomed.} h4
26. Rxc6 {Converting the extra pawn still requires some effort but provided a
minimum of technique, the outcome of the game is clear already.} Rd8 {Black
keeps the h-pawn in the hope of generating some counterplay.} ({If} 26... hxg3
27. hxg3 Rd8 28. R1c5 Rxc5 29. Nxc5 $18) 27. g4 $1 {Turning the h4-pawn into a
permanent weakness.} (27. R1c5 Rxc5 28. Nxc5 {would have offered Black some
vague hopes after} h3+ 29. Kxh3 Rd2 30. Ra6 Rxf2 31. Rxa7) 27... Rd2 28. R6c2
Rxc2 29. Rxc2 e6 30. Nc5 Be7 31. Nd3 {Since Black is busy keeping the
queenside majority under control, Ulf transfers his knight to the opposite
wing in order to support a new offence.} Bf8 (31... Ra3 32. Ne5 Bf6 33. Nc4 Ra6
34. f4 g5 35. Kf3 $18) 32. Ne1 Ra3 33. Nf3 a5 {Possibly a time trouble blunder.
} (33... Be7 34. Nd4 g5 35. Kf3 $18) 34. Nxh4 a4 35. bxa4 Rxa4 36. h3 Ra3 37.
Nf3 Ra5 38. Nd4 Kg8 39. Nb3 Ra3 40. Nd2 Ra4 41. Nf3 {Andersson must have
marked time in order to reach the time control and analyze the ending at
leisure after the adjournment.} Be7 (41... Be7 {This might have been the
secret move, after which Black resigned without resuming the game. A possible
continuation was:} 42. g5 Ra6 43. h4 Ra4 44. Nd4 Kg7 45. f4 Ra6 46. Kf3 Ra3 47.
Rc7 Kf8 48. Nc6 Bd6 (48... Bc5 49. Ne5 $18) 49. Ra7 $18) 1-0

