1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Rc1 c6 8. Bd3
a6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Qc2 Re8 11. O-O Nf8 12. Rfe1 Be6 13. a3 Nh5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7
15. Na4 Rad8 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. b4 Nf6 18. a4 Ne4 19. b5 axb5 20. axb5 Ng5 21. Nd2
Rd6 22. bxc6 bxc6 23. Ra1 Rh6 24. Nf1 Qf6 25. Ng3 Rh4 26. f4 Nge6 27. Nxe6 Qxe6
28. Rac1 Bd7 {We have a strategic fight typical for the Karlsbad structure.
White's minority's attack has created a chronical weakness on c6, while Black
tries to keep the position balanced with kingside counterplay. However, it is
obvious that Black's coordination is far from perfect. The queen is placed in
front of the rook and bishop, making the corresponding batteries less effective.
But Black's main problem is that his h4-rook is isolated from its colleagues.}
29. Bf5 {The start of a simplifying maneuver.} ({A player with a different
style might have chosen} 29. Nf5 Rg4 (29... Rh5 30. g4 $18) 30. h3 Rg6 31. Qf2
Rf6 32. g4 $16 {, when Black's pieces would have felt very uncomfortable.})
29... Qf6 30. Bxd7 Nxd7 31. Qf5 $1 {As strange as it may seem, Black does not
have adequate defenses after this move. The rook will never be able to return
into play effectively.} (31. Qxc6 $2 {would lead just to a pawn exchange:} Qxc6
32. Rxc6 Rxf4 $1 $11) 31... Re6 {The alternatives are no better.} (31... Qxf5
32. Nxf5 Rg4 (32... Rh5 33. g4 $18) 33. Nd6 $1 ({Preparing the capture on c6 as
} 33. Rxc6 {fails to} Rxf4 $1) 33... Re6 34. Rxc6 {White has won an important
pawn as} Rxf4 {runs into} 35. Rc8+ Nf8 36. Ra1 {, dooming the f8-knight, for
instance} Rxe3 37. g3 {preparing the king's escape.} Rf6 38. Raa8 Re1+ 39. Kg2
Re2+ 40. Kh3 Rh6+ 41. Kg4 f5+ 42. Kf3 $18) ({Or if} 31... Qd6 32. Nh5 {,
threatening to trap the rook with g2-g3, as} g6 {allows} 33. Qxd7 $1 Qxd7 34.
Nf6+) 32. Qxf6 Rxf6 (32... Nxf6 {does not make much of a difference:} 33. Nf5 (
{Even better than} 33. Ra1 {when Black could play} g6 {, avoiding immediate
disaster, even though the h4-rook would remain imprisoned.}) 33... Rh5 34. Ra1
h6 ({Or if} 34... Re8 35. Nd6 Rd8 36. Ra7 Rf8 37. Rc7 Ne8 38. Rxc6 {wins a
pawn. In case of the knight exchange, the d5-pawn would also be doomed as the
rook is not too stable on the fifth rank in view of the possible g2-g4. And if}
Rh6 39. Nf5 $1 Rxc6 40. Ne7+ Kh8 41. Nxc6 {with a technically won ending due
to the presence of knights on board.}) 35. Ng3 {The knight jumps are a bit
confusing but effective, eventually resulting in the rook being trapped.} Rh4
36. h3 {Preparing the later g2-g4.} Ne4 37. Nf5 Rh5 38. g4 Rxh3 39. Kg2 $18)
33. Rc3 Kf8 34. Ra1 Ke7 35. Ra7 g6 {Sokolov must have played this with a
painful feeling, as his rook remains arrested.} ({But if} 35... Rhh6 36. Rb3 {
, the only way to defend the knight would be Rd6, more or less forcing ...
g7-g6 anyway in order to avoid Nf5+.}) 36. Rc7 {Winning a pawn with a black
rook completely out of play is a good practical decision.} ({But White could
also continue with his attack:} 36. Rb3 Rd6 37. Rbb7 Ke6 38. Nf1 $5 $18 {
followed by Nd2 and the knight's transfer to c5.}) 36... Re6 37. R7xc6 Rxc6 38.
Rxc6 Nf6 39. h3 Nh5 40. Ne2 Ng7 (40... Ng7 {After reaching the time control,
Black resigned without waiting for} 41. Nc3 Rh5 42. Kh2 {followed by g2-g4 and
the loss of the second pawn.}) 1-0

