1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O Nbd7 7. c4 b6 8. Nc3
Bb7 9. d3 c5 10. e3 Re8 11. Qe2 Bf8 12. d4 cxd4 13. exd4 Rc8 14. Rac1 Bb4 15.
Ne5 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Ba6 17. Rd1 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. Qd2 Nxe5 20. cxd5 exd5 21.
Rxc8 Bxc8 22. Qxd5 Qxd5 23. Rxd5 Ng6 {White's bishops' pair in an open
position offer him a stable advantage. However, in the absence of chronical
black weaknesses, the defensive cooperation between the knight and bishop
should not be underestimated when evaluating the endgame. At this height of
the game White cannot claim a forced win yet, but it would be irritating for
him if the game ended in a draw.} 24. h4 {Gaining space, avoiding back rank
problems and preparing to push back the knight in due time.} Be6 25. Rd6 h6 ({
Black discarded} 25... h5 {due to the fact that in the long run, the pawn
could become weak. But this would be a more principled kingside setup, trying
to maintain the stability on the light squares. If} 26. Bf3 Bg4 27. Bd5 Nf8 $14
{, preparing ...Be6.}) 26. Bb7 {The start of an interesting phase in which
Andersson will use his bishops to restrict the enemy rook's activity, while he
will also slowly advance his queenside pawns. The last slightly mysterious
move prevents ...Rc8.} Bf5 27. Bc3 {Preventing ...Re1+, just in case, but also
preparing to support the queenside pawns' advance.} Nf8 28. b4 {For the time
being Black's queenside is quite solid, so White prepares to weaken it with
a4-a5 in order to create a target.} f6 29. a4 Re7 {The rook tries to free
itself from the light-squared bishop's domination - as we will see, without
much success.} (29... Re2 {fails to offer Black counterplay after} 30. a5 bxa5
31. bxa5 Rc2 $6 32. Bd2 $1 $18 {followed by Be3 and the the a7-pawn falls.})
30. Bd5+ Be6 ({More natural than} 30... Kh7 {, which would take the king away
from the center.}) 31. Bc6 {Continuing to dominate the rook by preventing ...
Rd7 or the activation along the c-file.} Kf7 {This offers White an important
tempo to continue his attack.} (31... Bd7 $5 {was an important alternative.}
32. a5 ({White's domination after} 32. b5 Bxc6 33. bxc6 {is illusory:} Rc7 34.
h5 Kf7 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ge6c5] followed by ...Ne6-c5. Optically this looks
dangerous for Black and it must have been the reason why he refrained from the
bishop exchange.}) 32... bxa5 33. bxa5 Bxc6 34. Rxc6 Rd7 ({Due to his piece
placement Black has no time to consolidate the kingside with} 34... h5 $2 35.
Rc8 $1 Rf7 36. Bb4 g6 37. Ra8 Kg7 {Now 38.Ð¾ Pc5 would win the a7-pawn and most
probably the game, but the most clear-cut win is} 38. Bxf8+ $1 Rxf8 39. Rxa7+
Kh6 40. a6 {The pawn will reach the seventh rank soon, which makes White's win
trivial.}) 35. h5 $14) 32. a5 ({Ulf correctly evaluates that he does not have
the time to carry out the attack in the most systematic way:} 32. b5 Nd7 33. a5
Nb8 $1 {and White either loses his stability or accepts the transposition to
an ending with opposite-colored bishops.}) 32... bxa5 33. bxa5 Rc7 34. Bb4 {
White unpins his c6-bishop and creates some potential threats against the
enemy king (Rf8# as in a line below)} Bd7 $6 {Only after this move Black has
serious problems. By clearing the e6-square he chooses the wrong trajectory
for the knight.} (34... Ng6 {, planning either ...Ne5 or ...Nd7 was better:}
35. h5 Ne5 36. Rd8 {Threatening Rf8#} Nd7 37. Be4 f5 38. Bd3 Rb7 39. Bd6 Rb3 {
and in connection with ...Rb1+ and ...Bd5 Black gets reasonable counterplay.})
35. Bf3 $1 ({This time White rightly refrains from the intermediate check} 35.
Bd5+ {, which would just help Black to return onto the right path with} Be6)
35... g6 {Black tries to stabilize the kingside, but this is only partly
possible as the f6-square will be weak now. But the rook's final destination
is the back rank, in order to get access to the a-pawn.} 36. Bd2 $1 {The start
of a new regrouping after which both White bishops will target the queenside.}
h5 37. Be3 Bc8 38. Rd3 {The series of unexpected moves continues. As in the
long run, Black's best chance to get some relief is connected with ...Bb7,
White redirects his rook to b3, in order to prevent that.} Ne6 ({This was not
a good moment for} 38... Bb7 {due to} 39. Bxb7 Rxb7 40. Rd6 $1 $18 {[%cal
Gd6a6] followed by Ra6. Amazing rook maneuvering fourth and backward!}) 39. Rb3
Ke7 40. Rb8 Kd7 41. Ra8 a6 42. Bb6 {At this height of the game White has
excellent winning chances already. The a6-pawn is doomed and the kingside is
weak. When White will win the a6-pawn, the entire sixth rank will be in danger.
Black's main survival chance is based on central activity.} Rc4 43. Ra7+ Kd6
44. Rf7 ({Now and on the next move} 44. Be2 {was simpler.}) 44... Ke5 45. Kg2
g5 $2 {This makes things simpler for White as he wins a kingside pawn while
the a6-pawn remains a permanent target.} ({Black's only chance to put up
resistance was} 45... Nd4 46. Re7+ $1 {An intermediate check causing Black to
get under a pin.} Be6 ({Forced as the other pin arising after} 46... Kd6 47.
Re4 {would be deadly.}) 47. Bb7 Nc6 48. Re8 Nb4 {For the time being Black
keeps his position together, but his minor pieces are immobile.} 49. Be3 $1 {
Another strong bishop retreat, aiming to attack the knight but also to create
side threats on the kingside.} Kd6 ({Evacuating the king from the dangerous
area. If} 49... Rc2 {, preventing Bd2, White has} 50. Bf4+ Kf5 51. Kg1 $1 {
. and the threat f2-f3 followed by Be4 mate forces Black to take desperate
measures like} g5 52. hxg5 fxg5 $2 53. Rf8+ Kg6 54. Be4+ Kg7 55. Bxc2 Kxf8 56.
Bd6+ $18) 50. Ra8 Ke5 51. Bd2 Bd5+ {Black looks for saving chances in a rook
ending with a pawn down.} 52. Bxd5 Kxd5 ({Since this loses mathematically,
keeping the knights makes some sense:} 52... Nxd5 53. Rxa6) 53. Bxb4 Rxb4 54.
Rxa6 Ke5 55. Ra8 Ra4 56. a6 Kf5 57. a7 {This is one of the cases when White
wins with his pawn on the seventh rank as his king has access to... h6!} Ra3
58. f3 {Preventing ...Kg4.} Ra2+ 59. Kf1 Ra4 60. Ke2 Ra3 61. Kd2 Ra4 62. Kc3
Ra6 63. Kb4 Ra1 64. Kc5 ({The attempt to expose the enemy king with} 64. g4+ {
fails to} Kf4 $1 $11) 64... Ra2 65. Kd6 Rd2+ (65... Ra1 66. Rc8 $1 Ra6+ 67. Rc6
Rxa7 68. Rc5#) 66. Ke7 Ra2 67. Kf7 Ra1 68. Kg7 Ra2 69. Kh6 Ra1 70. Rb8 Rxa7 71.
Rb5+ Ke6 72. Kxg6 Ra3 73. Rf5 $18) ({Other moves do not help much:} 45... Rc1
46. Be2 Rc3 (46... Rc2 47. Bd3 Rc3 48. Bxg6 $18) 47. Ra7 $18) (45... Rc2 46.
Bb7 Bxb7+ 47. Rxb7 {wins the a6-pawn soon.}) 46. Rh7 gxh4 47. Rxh5+ f5 48. Rxh4
{The rest is more of a formality.} Rc2 49. Rh1 Bd7 50. Re1+ Kf6 51. Re2 Rc1 52.
Be3 Rc4 53. Rd2 Bb5 54. Rd6 Ke7 55. Rb6 Ra4 56. Rb7+ Kf6 57. Bd2 Ra3 58. Rb6
Rd3 (58... Ke5 59. Bb7 $18) 59. Bc1 Rd7 60. Be3 (60. g4 $5 fxg4 61. Bxg4 Bc4
62. f4 Ke7 63. Ba3+ Kf7 64. Bd6 $18) 60... Ke7 $2 {Allowing a small
combination.} ({After} 60... Bc4 {White might have had to switch to the plan
mentioned above.}) 61. Rxb5 axb5 62. a6 Rd3 63. a7 Nc7 64. Bb6 Rxf3 65. Kxf3
Na8 66. Ba5 Ke6 67. Kf4 Kf6 68. f3 Ke6 69. Kg5 1-0

