1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O e6 6. Nc3 a6 7. b3 Be7 8. d4
cxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Ba3 Nc6 11. Qf4 d5 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Rfd1 Qb8 14. Qxb8+
Rxb8 15. cxd5 Nfxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Rac1 Rb7 {White is perfectly developed
and controls both open files. In case of a rook invasion, Black's queenside
pawns will be weak.  Black's main defender is the bishop, which makes the next
move just natural.} 18. Ne5 {This not only starts the fight for the d-file but
also brings the knight closer to c6 and c4.} Bxg2 (18... f6 {is best answered
with} 19. e4 Bxb3 20. axb3 fxe5 21. Rd6 Kf7 22. Bh3 $16 {White will retrieve
the pawn, maintaining very active play and the better structure.}) (18... Ra7
19. e4 Ba8 {is flexible but passive.} 20. a4 {Taking measures against ...b6-b5,
which would make the queenside less vulnerable.} f6 ({Black needs to drive
away the knight as} 20... O-O 21. Nd7 {loses a pawn. This is one of the
moments when White's domination can be felt quite clearly, as the knight jumps
deep in the enemy territory at his leisure.}) 21. Nc4 Nc8 {And now White has
two ways of winning a pawn.} 22. Nxb6 $5 ({Or, alternatively,} 22. Nd6+ Nxd6
23. Rxd6 Ke7 24. Rxb6) 22... Nxb6 23. a5 {The knight cannot move because of
Rc8+ winning the h8-rook, so White will get a very strong pawn on b6. In both
lines, the weakness of the e6-square is also relevant.}) 19. Kxg2 O-O 20. Rd6 {
Everything is prepared for the invasion now.} h6 {Black defends rather
passively.} ({But even after the more principled} 20... g5 {White would retain
a large advantage:} 21. Kf3 Kg7 22. e4 h5 23. h3 Ng6 24. Nxg6 Kxg6 25. Rcc6
Rfb8 26. Ke3 $16 {possibly followed by f4-f5 with pressure on both wings.}) 21.
e4 {Restricting the enemy knight, which is left almost without useful moves.}
Re8 22. Kf3 {With the pawn on e4 the king can advance to e3 unhindered.} Ra8
23. Ke3 a5 24. Rcd1 b5 $2 {This loses a pawn. Gheorghiu must have hoped he
would get counterplay, but Andersson's virtuosity in handling the knight will
keep events under control.} (24... g5 {is more logical, but far from
satisfactory.} 25. Rd7 Rab8 26. R1d6 Kg7 27. Rxb7 Rxb7 28. Nc4 Nc8 29. Rc6 Rb8
30. Rc7 Kf6 31. f4 $18 {Black's pieces are completely paralyzed and he has no
remedy to the threat Ne5.}) 25. Rd8+ Rxd8 26. Rxd8+ Kh7 27. Nxf7 Nc6 28. Rc8 $1
{Forcing the knight to give up the control over e5 in order to prepare the
next forced sequence.} Nb4 29. Rh8+ Kg6 30. Ne5+ Kf6 31. f4 {The knight has
returned in the center with great effect.} Ke7 ({The point is that} 31... Nxa2
{loses the rook to.} 32. Rf8+ Ke7 33. Rf7+) 32. Rg8 Kd6 33. Rd8+ Ke7 34. Ra8
Nxa2 35. Rxa5 {White has retained the extra pawn and the better structure.} Nc3
36. Kd3 b4 37. Ra6 Nb5 38. Nc6+ Kd7 39. Nd4 Nxd4 40. Kxd4 Ke7 41. g4 {and
Black resigned without resuming the game after adjournment. Apart from the
extra pawn White has superior activity and a lot of space, while e6 is
chronically weak.} 1-0

