1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 f6
8. Be3 e5 9. Nd2 Be6 10. Bc4 Bxc4 (10... Kf7 $1 11. Kc2 Nd7 12. Rhd1 Be7 13. a4
Rhd8 14. b4 a5 15. Kb3 c6 $10 {Suba,M-Svidler,P/Linares/1994/0:1/43/}) 11. Nxc4
Nd7 {/\Bc5/} 12. b4 Nb6 (12... h5 13. Kc2 Bh6 14. Bxh6 Rxh6 15. Rhd1 O-O-O 16.
Na5 Rhh8 17. Rd3 $16 {Loginov,V-Sideif Sade,F/Aktiubinsk/1985/1:0/43/}) 13. Na5
O-O-O+ 14. Kc2 Be7 15. a3 f5 $6 16. Bxb6 $1 axb6 17. Nc4 Bf6 $2 {White's
knight is more active than the bishop, but the position is almost symmetrical
and Black seems to have some advantage in the center. In fact, the latter is
deceptive as there is no clear way to make progress. What White needs is a way
to open files for his rooks. Since Black has queenside weaknesses and the king
is placed on that part of the board, the plan initiated by the next move is
logical.} (17... fxe4 18. Rae1 Rhf8 19. Rhf1 Bh4 20. Rxe4 (20. g3 Bg5 21. Rxe4
b5 $1 22. Ne3 Bxe3 23. Rxe3 $14) 20... Rxf2+ 21. Rxf2 Bxf2 22. Rxe5 $14) 18. a4
$1 Bg7 19. Rhe1 Rhe8 20. b5 {Comfortably preparing a4-a5.} f4 $6 {A curious
decision. By releasing the tension Black admits that he has a "bad" bishop. He
also gives up the chances for counterplay along the f-file (especially after
f2-f3, ...fxe4, fxe4) and frees the rook from the task of defending e4.
Black's main idea might have been securing the center in order to prepare the
king's evacuation.} (20... fxe4 $6 21. Rxe4 Rf8 22. f3 Rf4 23. Rae1 {offers
White very pleasant play against the numerous black pawns blocked on dark
squares.}) ({But Black should have evacuated the kingside before it was too
late:} 20... Kd7 21. a5 bxa5 22. Nxa5 Rb8 23. Kb3 Ke6 24. Nc4 $14 {True, his
position remains a bit dangerous, as e5 is submitted to constant pressure,
which can be increased with Ra5, or if the e8-rook leaves the e-file by exf5+
followed by Nxe5 and f2-f4. And yet, the only things he should really avoid is
blocking the kingside with} f4 $2 25. b6 $1 c6 (25... cxb6 26. Nxb6 $16 {
yields the d5 square to the knight.}) 26. Red1 Bf8 (26... Red8 $2 27. Rxd8 Rxd8
28. Ra7 Rb8 29. Na5 {loses the b7-pawn.}) 27. Ra5 Kf6 28. Rd7 $16 {, with an annoying initiative. In order to save the b7-pawn Black would have to give up
the e5-pawn.}) 21. a5 bxa5 ({Stabilizing the structure with} 21... Re6 22. axb6
cxb6 {allows the intrusion through the eighth rank.} 23. Ra8+ Kc7 24. Rxd8 Kxd8
25. Ra1 Kc7 26. Ra8 $16) 22. Rxa5 {Even though Black seems to be well
regrouped he can do little for the queenside's and the king's safety. This is
a common situation in middlegames with an attack for one of the sides. One of
the reasons for this situation here is the total passivity of the bishop.} b6 (
{Now is not a good moment for the king's evacuation as this would leave the
queenside insufficiently defended:} 22... Kd7 23. Ra7 Rb8 24. Rd1+ Ke6 25. Na5
b6 26. Nc6 Rbc8 27. Rb7 Bf8 28. Na7 $18) 23. Ra7 {Threatening Nxb6.} Bf6 (23...
Re6 {loses material after} 24. Ra8+ Kd7 25. Rd1+) 24. Rea1 Re6 25. R1a6 {
Threatening Na5-c6. The attack along the a-file is developing quickly with
simple moves.} Rde8 26. Kb3 {The kind of move which may be not absolutely
necessary, but cannot harm either. The king moves closer to the d5-square,
just in case all rooks get swapped.  The main plan consists of c4-c5,
preferably with the knight on d3.} Bd8 {This allows a rook regrouping typical
for Andersson.} ({But neutral moves such as} 26... h5 {would not have crossed
White's main plan.} 27. Nb2 Rd6 28. c4 Red8 (28... Rd2 29. c5 {followed by
c5-c6 wins quickly.}) 29. c5 bxc5 30. Nc4 Rxa6 31. bxa6 Kb8 32. Rb7+ Kc8 33.
Na5 $18 {followed by a6-a7.}) 27. Ra8+ Kd7 28. Ra2 $5 {A typical Ulf retreat,
planning the rook's transfer to d5.} ({But even stronger would have been} 28.
R6a7 {planning Rb8 followed by Nxb6+, and if} Rf6 29. Rb8 Ree6 30. Ra2 Be7 31.
Rd2+ Bd6 32. f3 g5 33. Rd5 {At the very least White always has Nxd6, winning
either the e5- or the b6-pawn.}) 28... Bf6 29. Rd2+ Ke7 30. Ra7 Rc8 31. Rd5 {
After this regrouping, the plan based on c4-c5 is even stronger.} Ke8 32. h3 $5
{Another generally useful move, taking the pawn out of the bishop's range.} Ke7
{Black can do little more than waiting.} 33. Nb2 Ke8 34. Nd3 Bg7 (34... c6 35.
Rdd7 $18) 35. c4 {Finally the signal for the attack.} Bf6 36. c5 bxc5 37. Nxc5
Re7 38. Ra6 Bh8 {As we can see, after the pawn break White obtained even
better communication between the wings, further strengthening his domination.}
39. Kc4 Bg7 40. f3 $5 {The c7-pawn is doomed anyway so White makes the last
waiting move, inviting his opponent to make things easier for him.} Rb8 $6 41.
Ne6 Bf6 42. Rc6 $1 (42. Rc6 Rc8 (42... Rb7 43. Rd8+ Kf7 44. Rf8#) 43. b6 $18)
1-0

