1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 Nc6 7. Bb5 Rc8 8. c4
dxc4 9. bxc4 e6 10. Bxf6 $1 {Simplifying to a very pleasant ending.} Qxf6 11.
Qxf6 gxf6 12. Nc3 Kd8 13. Bxc6 $1 {This corresponds only partly with Ulf's
preference to play with knights against bishops. In fact, after unpinning the
knight, Black intended to leave the b5-bishop out of play, for example with
Ne5.} Rxc6 {Time has come to evaluate the ending. White's structure is more
compact while Black has serious kingside weaknesses. The queenside situation
also favors White, who can set up pressure along the b-file and sustain his
attack with the advance of the a-pawn. The only practical problem is generated
by the fact that the knight is placed on a dark square, making it vulnerable
to the enemy bishop. But Andersson's virtuosity in using this piece will solve
the problem during the next phase.} 14. Rb1 Kc8 15. Ke2 f5 $6 {Optically this
seems to be the best way to arrange the kingside pawns, as the bishop has many
open diagonals now while the knight is a bit restricted. But the last move
offers White an easy target.} ({More cautious would have been} 15... h5 {
planning ...f6-f5 and if} 16. g4 {then just a neutral move such as} Be7 $14)
16. g4 $1 Bg7 ({Black has to accept the weakening of his double pawns as after
} 16... fxg4 17. hxg4 {White gets too much pressure on the h-file. If} h6 18.
g5 $5 {the black rooks' lack of communication offers White strong initiative.}
Bg7 19. gxh6 Rxh6 20. Rxh6 Bxh6 21. Rh1 Bg5 22. Rh7 f5 ({Black has to weaken
his seventh rank as after} 22... Rc7 23. Nb5 Rd7 {White has a pleasant choice
between 24.î ..xa7+ and} 24. Rxf7 Rxf7 25. Nd6+) 23. Nb5 Kb8 24. Rh8+ Rc8 25.
Rxc8+ Kxc8 26. Nxa7+ {with every chance to win due to the extra pawn and the
more flexible structure.}) 17. Nb5 $1 {The knight evacuates the unfavorable
square with a gain of time. As difficult as this may seem to believe, the knight
is heading for...f3, a stable location on a light square.} (17. gxf5 Bxc3 18.
dxc3 exf5 $11) 17... Kb8 {This is the most natural move. Black simply intends
to send the knight back with ...a7-a6.} ({Had he anticipated the glorious
trajectory of this piece, he might have considered to prevent it with} 17...
Ra6 {Play would have been a bit tenser than in the game, but White would
have maintained a clear plus with accurate moves:} 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Rhg1 Bf6
20. a3 {The knight's retreat has been cut off, but preparing ...a7-a6 takes
some time, which White can use to activate his rooks.} Kd7 21. Rg3 Rc8 ({Black
has to overdefend c7 as} 21... Ra4 {is premature due to} 22. Rf3 Ke6 23. Nc7+)
22. Rb3 Ke6 23. Rd3 Be5 ({Defending e5.} 23... Ra4 {still does not work:} 24.
Rd6+ Ke7 25. Rd5 Rxc4 26. Rxf5 {and Black's whole position is hanging.}) 24. f4
Bf6 25. Rg1 $5 $16 {After having forced Black to regroup, the rook switches to
the queenside. The global plan is Rb1-b3 followed by Rd5 and Rbd3. Since Black
has to defend c7, d6, a7 and, for the time, being, g7, he is practically
immobile (if not in some sort of Zugzwang.)}) 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Rhg1 Bf6 20.
Rg3 a6 21. Na3 $1 {Hort might have considered this a small success, as "all
knights stand badly on the edge of the board". Besides, the c3-square,
offering access to d5, is denied. But due to the static character of the
position, the knight has no problems reaching f3.  At the same time, the last
move (which Black could probably not avoid in the long run anyway, but could
have delayed a bit) creates new weaknesses, which will allow White to play on
two wings.} Be5 22. Rg5 Rf6 23. Nc2 Re8 24. Ne1 Bd6 25. Nf3 {White has many
possible kingside plans. While Rg7 followed by Ng5 is one of them, I would
prefer the prophylactic d2-d3 followed by Nh4, in order to meet ...f5-f4 with
e3-e4. All these explain the next move, opening the communication between both
wings along the fifth rank.} f4 26. Rd5 Kc7 27. a4 {Having reached a maximum
of activity on the kingside and in the center, Ulf starts to make queenside
progress.} Kc6 {This makes things simpler for White, as c5 becomes a
comfortable target now.} ({More natural is} 27... b6 {when White might have
focused on the kingside, for the time being, leaving the thoughts about how to
exploit the queenside weaknesses for later.} 28. Rh5 h6 29. Rg1 Kc6 30. d3 {
Threatening e3-e4.} fxe3 31. fxe3 Bc7 32. e4 $16) 28. a5 $1 fxe3 ({Hort might
have initially considered White's last move far from one-sided as after} 28...
Bc7 $2 {the pawn seems to be in need of protection. But White wins with} 29. d4
$1 Bd6 (29... cxd4 $2 30. Nxd4#) (29... Bxa5 30. Rxc5+ {loses the bishop.}) 30.
Rb6+ Kc7 31. Rxc5+ Bxc5 32. Rxf6 $18) 29. Rb6+ Kc7 30. fxe3 h6 $2 {Possibly a
time trouble blunder.} ({Black should have defended his rook with} 30... Rg6 {
, thus keeping the c5-pawn. There is some point to Hort's last move, though,
as White now has} 31. Ng5 Be7 (31... Bf8 32. Rxg6 fxg6 33. Nxh7 $18) 32. Ne4 (
32. Rxg6 fxg6 33. Nxh7 Rh8 34. Ng5 $16 {may be less clear.}) 32... Rc8 (32...
Rxb6 33. axb6+ Kxb6 34. Re5 $18 {followed by Nf6, winning the exchange.}) 33.
Rb1 Kb8 34. Rf1 Rg7 (34... Rg2+ 35. Kd3 {does not change much.}) 35. Rff5 $18 {
and White can a pawn at his leisure.}) 31. Rxc5+ Kb8 32. Rd5 {With such a
strong central pawn mass the win is a formality already.} Kc7 33. Nd4 Rg6 34.
Rf5 f6 35. Rd5 Be5 36. Rc5+ Kd8 37. Nf3 Rg2+ 38. Kd3 Re7 39. Nxe5 fxe5 40. Rxh6
1-0

