1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 c5
$6 {This move unnecessarily weakens the queenside. Black should have aimed for
a structure with ...e7-e5 and keep the queen's bishop pawn on c7 or c6 in
order to avoid a weakening of the d5-square.} 8. Be3 b6 9. a4 {Immediately
starting the attack against the newly created weaknesses. Due to his lack of
queenside development, Black cannot afford to allow a4-a5.  It should be added
that the central situation also slightly favors White, as he can think of a
way of advancing his e- and f-pawns, obstructing the bishop g7.} Nc6 10. Bb5
Bd7 {Black prevents the further advance of the a-pawn, but places the bishop
on a vulnerable square.} ({True,} 10... Bb7 11. a5 O-O-O+ 12. Ke2 $14 {would
also be quite pleasant for White.}) 11. Kc2 Bg7 12. Rhd1 {This not only
prevents Black from castling but also renews the pin along the a4-e8 diagonal
and the threat a4-a5. After the latter, White needs to take care of the
possibility Nb4+, which however does not always work.} a6 {Black could not
stand the pressure and decided to drive away the bishop. But this creates new
weaknesses.} ({A neutral move such as} 12... f6 $6 {, aiming to get some
control in the center, allows} 13. a5 {, since after} Nb4+ 14. cxb4 Bxb5 {
White has} 15. axb6 $18 {, and the a7-pawn is pinned.}) (12... Rc8 {avoids
this problem but does not help Black's development.} 13. Kc1 $1 ({Reneweing
the threat a4-a5.} 13. a5 $2 Nb4+ $1 14. cxb4 Bxb5 {is perfectly fine for
Black.}) 13... Rc7 14. Bf4 e5 {This is a success for White already, as Black
has weakened the d5-square, but actually, taking the pawn is entirely possible:
} (14... Rb7 15. Ba6 $18) 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxe5 Bxe4 17. Nc4 Re7 18. Nd6+ Kf8
19. f3 Bc6 20. Nc8 Rd7 21. a5 $18 {Black's queenside is doomed and his
kingside underdeveloped.}) 13. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] Threatening Bxf7+.} Bg4 {This
looks like the simplest short-term solution, but in the long run, White's
bishops' pair will prove to be very strong. Despite apparency, the exchange on
f3 strengthens White's structure as he will now be able to play f3-f4 and
e4-e5.} (13... Ra7 {does not threaten castling yet.} 14. Be2 $5 {Planning
Nd2-c4.} Na5 (14... O-O 15. Bxa6 $16) 15. b4 ({The more peaceful} 15. Nd2 {
also ensures White an advantage:} O-O 16. Nc4 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 Bc8 18. Rd2 $16)
15... Nb7 (15... cxb4 16. Bxb6 $18) 16. b5 $16) (13... e6 {looks more solid
but weakens the d6-square and leaves Black with the task of clearing the
c6-square for his bishop.} 14. Bf4 Na5 15. Nd2 Bc6 16. f3 Ra7 (16... Nxc4 17.
Nxc4 b5 18. axb5 Bxb5 {Otherwise Black loses the b5 pawn after Rxa8 and Nd6+.} 19. Nb6 Ra7 20. c4 Bc6 21. Ra5 $18) (16... O-O 17. Bc7 Nxc4 18. Nxc4 b5
19. Nb6 Ra7 20. Bd6 Re8 21. axb5 Bxb5 22. c4 Bc6 23. Ra5 $18) 17. Bd6 {Black
has several weaknesses on the dark squares and he has not solved the problem of
his king yet.}) 14. h3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 O-O 16. f4 Ra7 (16... e5 {weakens the
d5-square chronically and can be met in many ways. Personally, I would play} 17.
f5 $5 $18 {with a large advantage all over the board.}) 17. e5 {White has a
consistent advantage. He has more space in the center and the d-file is his.
Black's queenside is hanging and the g7-bishop is out of play.} a5 {This
simplifies White's task as the king will be able to march in through the
weakened light squares. But there was no adequate solution to Black's problems
already.} (17... e6 18. b4 cxb4 19. a5 $16) (17... Na5 18. Be2 Rc8 19. Rd2 $16
{followed by the invasion along the d-file.}) 18. Rd2 e6 19. Rad1 Rc8 20. Kb3
$1 {The signal to the final attack.} Bf8 21. Bb5 Rcc7 {This allows White to
clear the path for his king with the next exchange.} ({But the regrouping} 
21... Ne7 {would not stop the invasion either:} 22. Rd8 Rac7 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24.
Rd7 Nf5 25. Kc4 $1 ({It is better to block the c-pawn as after the hurried} 25.
Rb7 Nxe3 26. fxe3 c4+ 27. Bxc4 Bc5 {Black has some chances to put up some
resistance. Still, after} 28. e4 $18 {White can combine the queenside plan
with a kingside attack.}) 25... Be7 26. Rb7 Bd8 27. Ba6 Ra8 28. Rd7 Bh4 29. Kb5
Rd8 30. Rxd8+ Bxd8 31. Kc6 Nxe3 32. fxe3 Kf8 {The presence of
opposite-colored bishops does not save Black, as he loses two important
queenside pawns.} 33. Kd7 Bh4 34. Kc7 Bf2 35. Kxb6 Bxe3 36. Kxa5 $18) 22. Bxc6
Rxc6 23. Kc4 Be7 24. Rd7 Rcc7 25. Rxc7 Rxc7 26. Kb5 {The rest is agony.} Rc8
27. Rd7 Kf8 28. Kxb6 Ke8 29. Rb7 Bd8+ 30. Kb5 c4 31. Bc5 1-0

