1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bg7 5. e4 Nc6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8.
Be2 d6 9. O-O a5 10. f3 Nd7 11. Ndb5 Nc5 12. Qd2 a4 13. Rfd1 Qa5 14. Rac1 Be6 {
White has the typical Maroczy bind space advantage in a static position.
Black's queenside achievements are optically pleasing, but not of much
concrete relevance.} 15. Nd5 {White is heading for an ending, probably
anticipating the exchange sacrifice already.} Qxd2 16. Rxd2 Bxd5 17. cxd5 Nb4 {
Black has some queenside pressure and the c5-knight seems to ensure him some
stability. But the next move puts things into place.} 18. Rxc5 $1 {White
eliminates one of Black's key pieces in the best possible way.} (18. Bxc5 {
would have retained some advantage but the presence of opposite-coloured
bishops would have offered Black excellent chances for successful defence:}
dxc5 19. f4 (19. Rxc5 $2 Bh6 $1 {wins an exchange.}) 19... Nxa2 20. Rxc5 Rfc8
$14 {and things are not entirely clear.}) (18. a3 $2 {runs into} Nb3) 18...
dxc5 19. Bxc5 Nxa2 20. Bxe7 Rfc8 {White has a pawn for the exchange and his
mobile center is likely to suffocate Black if handled accurately.} 21. f4 $6 {
An entirely excusable inaccuracy, since Black's main saving plan as revealed
in a few of the lines below, is anything but obvious. Optically and humanly,
the next move is the most logical, as it does not imply an important
commitment yet, even though the main plan is to place the pawns on f4, e5 and
d6.} ({The correct move order was} 21. d6 $1 Bf8 ({The plan recommended below
is less effective now as after} 21... Nc1 22. Bd1 Bf8 23. e5 Nb3 {White has}
24. Rd5 $16 {In the game this square would not be available.}) 22. Kf2 Nc1 23.
Nc7 Rab8 (23... Rxc7 24. Bxf8 Rd7 25. Bb5 $18) 24. Bb5 $18) 21... Bf8 ({This
is the first moment when the maneuver initiated by} 21... Nc1 {would maintain
approximate equality. The knight's trajectory is somewhat curious but the main
idea is to get closer to the e6-square in view of the probable d5-d6.} 22. Bd1
(22. d6 Nxe2+ 23. Rxe2 Bf8 {is unclear, as after} 24. e5 $2 {Black has} Bxe7
25. dxe7 Rc1+ $1 26. Kf2 Re8 {The intermediate check was essential in order to
avoid the double attack Nc7.}) 22... Nb3 23. Bxb3 axb3 24. d6 Bf8 25. Bf6 Bg7 {
Avoiding a repetition implies exchanging the bishops, when the vulnerability
of the b2-pawn offers Black counterchances.}) 22. d6 Nb4 $2 {Missing his
second and last chance.} (22... Nc1 $1 23. Bd1 Nb3 24. Rd5 Rc4 25. e5 Nc5 26.
g3 Ne6 27. Rd2 $44 {Black has achieved the best regrouping but White retains
entirely adequate compensation for the exchange. One important point is that
Black cannot free himself with} Bxe7 $2 28. dxe7 Re8 29. Nd6 $18) 23. Bh4 {
This was the type of position Andersson had been aiming for when sacrificing
the exchange. White has a crushing advantage now. His pawns supported by all
pieces are hard to stop.} Rc1+ 24. Kf2 Nc6 25. Nc7 a3 $5 {The only chance to
get some activity.} 26. bxa3 (26. Nxa8 $2 a2 $1) 26... Rxa3 27. e5 h6 {
Threatening to break White's pawn chain with ...g6-g5.} 28. Bf6 $1 Bg7 29. Be7
$1 Bf8 30. Nd5 {Stabilziing the position in the center.} Ra8 (30... Bxe7 $2 {
loses quickly to} 31. Nxe7+ Nxe7 32. dxe7 Ra8 33. Rd8+) 31. h4 {The feeling of
absolute control is a bit deceptive. White retains a big advantage after this
slow move, but after the correct defence Black still has chances of survival.}
(31. Bf3 $1 {was stronger, preparing to eliminate one of Black's defenders
with Bxc6 (as in both lines below).} Rca1 {The same as in the line recommended
below, exchanging one rook is the only attempt to get some relief.} 32. Bf6
R1a2 ({Or if} 32... Bg7 33. Ne7+ Kh7 34. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 35. d7 $18 {We see that
the light-squared bishop was not needed for sustaining the pawn, but it surely
helped it indirectly by exchanging on c6.}) 33. Rxa2 Rxa2+ 34. Ke3 Ra1 35. Nb6
$18 {, and everything is ready for Bxc6 followed by the advance of the d-pawn.}
) 31... Rc5 $2 {Not only failing to find the best plan but also creating a
simple geometrical motif.} ({Better was} 31... Rca1 {, preparing the rook
exchange, even though after} 32. h5 $16 {White's position remains very
promising.}) 32. Nf6+ Kg7 33. Bxf8+ Rxf8 34. Nd7 1-0

