1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 Nf6 7. e5 Nd5 8.
c4 Nc7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Ne6 11. Qh4 h6 12. Nc3 d6 13. Rd1 Bb7 14. Be3 c5 15.
Nd5 {Strategically, Black is doing fine, due to his compact structure and well
placed minor pieces. But White has certain pressure in the center and Black
cannot castle yet. The queen sacrifice implied by the next move aims to
neutralize the dynamic factors and keep the static trumps.} dxe5 $1 16. Nf6+
Bxf6 17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. Qg3 h5 {Andersson is not interested in keeping his
extra pawn, as his development is incomplete yet. Instead, he will be aiming
for an ending which, surprisingly, will be easier to play with black.} ({After
} 18... Nd4 19. Bxd4 exd4 20. Nd2 {, threatening Qc7,} Rc8 21. Qa3 a6 22. Nb3 {
White would maintain the initiative.}) 19. h4 O-O 20. Nxe5 Nd4 21. Bxd4 Rxd4
22. Re1 Rfd8 23. Qb3 {Pawns are equal, but after the next exchange Black's
rook and bishop will prove to be not weaker than the queen.} Be4 24. Nf3 ({
White could have maintained some tension with} 24. Qg3 {but he apparently was
afraid of playing against two bishops. After the game move Black not only wins
a pawn but also gets the sort of one-sided position Ulf is delighted with.})
24... Bxf3 25. Qxf3 {Black is perfectly centralized and with his next move he
can take either pawn on the fourth rank.} Rxc4 {From a practical point of view
the best. Black starts to systematically clear the path for the c-pawn. Even
though his queenside structure looks weak, his main trumps are his perfect
stability and the vulnerability of the f2-pawn. As revealed by the further
course of the game, taking the a7-pawn does not allow White to create
effective counterplay with his own a-pawn as Black's initiative develops more
quickly. The best thing White can hope for is to give perpetual check.} (25...
Bxh4 26. b3 Rd2 27. Re2 {would allow White to consolidate.}) 26. g3 {White
also takes the correct decision regarding which pawn to keep.} (26. b3 {would
prevent Black from creating a passed pawn on the c-file and also win the
a7-pawn, but it would leave his king weak:} Rxh4 27. Qb7 Rd2 28. Qxa7 ({The
intermediate} 28. g3 {does not change much:} Rhd4 29. Qxa7 Rc2 30. a4 Rdd2 31.
Rf1 Bd4 32. Qxe7 {Hoping for a perpetual check, but Black is not forced to take
on f2 yet.} Rb2 33. Qb7 Rd3 {Black wins the b3-pawn and soon the a4-pawn.
facing White with a difficult defensive task.}) 28... Bd4 29. Rf1 Kg7 {
Anticipating Qb8+ and threatening ...Rf4.} 30. Qxe7 (30. g3 Re4 {followed by ..
.Ree2 defends e7 and wins f2.}) (30. Qb8 Rxa2 {leaves White without his
queenside counterplay.}) 30... Rf4 $17 {White has no time to start his
counterplay with} 31. a4 $2 {due to} Rdxf2 32. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 33. Kh2 (33. Kf1 Bh4+
{wins the queen.}) 33... Rh4+ {and White has to give up his queen.}) 26... Rc2
27. Re2 Rxb2 28. Rxb2 Bxb2 {Black has a small material advantage already, but
since several of his pawns are hanging, White will win one of them back soon.
In the next phase of the game, it will be impossible to mechanically stop the
passed c-pawn, partly because the f2-square is also weak, a typical feature
for this kind of endings. White needs to create kingside counterplay with the
double pawn sacrifice g3-g4 followed by h4-h5 in order to weaken Black's king
and play for a perpetual.} 29. Qb7 $6 {This move indicates that White still
had ambitions. He obviously overestimated the force of his a-pawn.} (29. Qe3 $5
{would have won the e7-pawn and as a result, weakened Black's king's position
and made the plan based on g3-g4 more effective.} Rd1+ (29... c4 30. Qxe7 Rd2
31. Qc7 c3 {misses just one tempo to win as immediately after Black has
obstructed the long diagonal White can start the drawing maneuver:} 32. Qb8+
Kg7 33. Qe5+) 30. Kg2 Bd4 31. Qxe7 Rd2 {Things look dangerous already, but
White draws easily with} 32. g4 hxg4 33. Kg3 Rxa2 34. h5 $11) ({The immediate} 
29. g4 {is also possible:} hxg4 30. Qxg4 Rd5 {The only way to stabilize the
kingside.} 31. Qc8+ Kg7 32. Qb7 {This double attack forces Black to abandon
the fifth rank.} Rd2 33. Qxe7 Bd4 34. h5 $11) 29... Rd1+ {At this height of
the game both players seem to have been unaware of the importance of the
e7-pawn.} (29... Bf6 $1 $15 {would have offered better chances for a small but
stable advantage:} 30. Qc6 (30. Qxa7 $2 {allows Black to put into motion the
deadly mechanism without delay:} c4 31. Qc7 Rd1+ 32. Kg2 c3 33. a4 Rd2 34. a5
c2 35. a6 {White is close but not close enough. True, 35...Bb2 loses to 36.
Qb8+ but} Bd4 $1 $19 {stops the pawn and threatens ...Rxf2+ followed by ...Be3.
}) 30... Rd2 31. g4 (31. Qxc5 Rxa2 $17) 31... hxg4 32. h5 gxh5 (32... Rxa2 33.
hxg6 Ra1+ 34. Kg2 fxg6 35. Qxc5 {makes Black's chances problematic as his
pawns are not compact anymore.}) 33. Qxc5 g3 $5 34. Qxh5 gxf2+ 35. Kf1 Rd4 {
Preventing Qg4+ followed by Qc8+.} 36. Kxf2 e6 {The connected passed pawns
offer Black chances, as the a7-pawn is not edible:} 37. Qa5 Rd5 {, planning ...
a7-a5, and if} 38. Qxa7 $2 Bd4+) 30. Kg2 Bd4 31. Qxa7 $2 ({Once again, the
e7-pawn was more important:} 31. Qxe7 $1 Rd2 32. g4 hxg4 33. h5 $11) ({The
immediate} 31. g4 $1 {would have just transposed.}) 31... Rd2 ({Once again} 
31... e6 {might have been a bit more accurate, forcing White to find a few
accurate moves:} 32. g4 hxg4 33. Qe7 Rd2 34. h5 Kg7 (34... Rxf2+ 35. Kg3 Kg7
36. a4 $11) 35. Kg3 $3 {The only saving move, preparing h5-h6+.} ({If} 35. a4
c4 $19 {the pawn race is uneven.}) ({Inserting} 35. hxg6 Kxg6 {before} 36. Kg3
{allows} Rd3+ 37. Kxg4 f5+ 38. Kf4 $6 e5+) (35. h6+ $2 Kxh6 36. Qxf7 {is
premature due to} Rxf2+) 35... Bxf2+ (35... c4 36. h6+ Kxh6 37. Qxf7 $11) 36.
Kxg4 gxh5+ 37. Kxh5 Rd5+ 38. Kg4 Bd4 39. a4 c4 40. Kf3 c3 41. Qc7 $15 {Black's
advantage may be symbolic, as the a-pawn is for once relatively fast. Still,
Black does not risk anything, as he can give the bishop for the pawn, reaching
a simple fortress.}) 32. a4 $2 {The decisive mistake.} ({True, it was too late
for} 32. Qxe7 $2 c4 33. g4 c3 34. gxh5 c2 35. Qc7 gxh5 36. Kg3 Kg7 $19 {,
followed by ...Bb2 and ...c1D.}) ({But changing the move order would still
have saved the game:} 32. g4 $1 c4 33. Qa8+ Kg7 34. gxh5 c3 35. hxg6 c2 36.
gxf7 Rxf2+ 37. Kg3 c1=Q 38. Qg8+ Kh6 39. f8=Q+ Rxf8 40. Qxf8+ Kg6 41. Qxe7 $11)
32... c4 {The mechanism is unstoppable now.} 33. Qc7 c3 {A typical position
with a group of three pieces defending each other, making them invulnerable to
the queen.} 34. a5 Rxf2+ 35. Kh3 e5 36. Qc4 c2 37. a6 Be3 0-1

