{[#]After White's last move, 41.Neg1 intending Nh3, the g5-pawn is doomed. Is
Black really lost?} 41... e5 $1 {This central break saves the game.} (41... Nb8
$2 42. Nh3 Nc6 43. Nhxg5 Nb4 44. a3 Nc2 45. Nh3 Bc6 46. g5+ Kf5 47. g6 Be8 48.
Nf4 Nxa3 49. Ne5 Kf6 50. Nh5+ Ke7 51. g7 Bf7 52. Ng4 (52. Ng6+ $5 {is even
more convincing:} Kd8 53. Nf6 Nc2 54. Ne5 Ke7 55. Nxf7 Kxf7 56. g8=Q+) 52...
Nc2 53. Nhf6 $18 {Andersson,U-Barcza,G Hastings 1972 (1-0, 82)}) 42. Nh3 (42.
dxe5+ Nxe5 {offers White more of a symbolic advantage. True, his knight looks
stronger than the bishop, but g4 is a chronical weakness.}) 42... e4 43. Nfxg5
{The knights are immobile now, making any further progress impossible. The
fact that Black controls f3 is essential. The only chance would be Kg3-f4/h4,
but White is not in time for it.} Nf8 44. Kg3 Ng6 45. b4 Bc6 46. Nh7+ Kg7 47.
N7g5 (47. N3g5 {is rather risky, as the knights may become vulnerable.}) 47...
Kf6 $11 *

