{[#]White seems to have a slight endgame edge, due to the possible blockade on
d4. And yet, it is Black who can fight for an advantage!} 44... d4 $1 {Proving
once more that unblocked pawns have the natural tendency to advance. The last
move clears the a2-g8 diagonal, turning the b3-pawn into a weakness.} (44...
Bg4 $6 {prevents Nf3-d4 but does not offer more than equality.} 45. Bg2 Ke6 46.
Kf1 $11) 45. e4 (45. exd4 Nf5 46. b4 Nxd4 {offers Black the better ending, as
his king has better possibilities for rapid centralization and the white
queenside pawns are vulnerable.}) 45... f5 {Continuing to clear space in the
center.} 46. exf5 (46. e5 Ne4 47. Nc4 Ke7 {and White's position remains shaky.}
) 46... Bxf5 (46... Nxf5 $15) 47. Bg2 (47. Nf3 d3 48. Bxd3 Bxd3 49. Ne5+ Ke6
50. Nxd3 Kd5 51. Kf1 Kd4 52. Ke2 Kc3 53. b4 Kb3 54. a5 bxa5 55. bxa5 Ka4 56. a6
Kb5 {The outside passed pawn offers Black excellent chances.}) 47... Ke6 48.
Ba8 (48. Kf1 Ne8 $5 {even though left behind the scenes, this regrouping,
based on an initial retreat, is typical for Andersson.} 49. Ke2 Nf6 $15) 48...
Bc2 49. Nf3 d3 50. Kf1 Bd1 51. Nd4+ (51. Nd2 Ke5 $19) 51... Ke5 52. Nc6+ Kf6
53. Ke1 (53. Nd4 d2 54. Nf3 Bxb3 55. Nxd2 Bxa4 $19) 53... Bxb3 54. Nb4 Bxa4 $19
{Kortschnoj,V-Andersson,U Wijk aan Zee 1971 (0-1, 73)} *

