{[#]White has the bishops' pair and a target on d5. Your move.} 42. f5+ $1 {
It is essential to open the g3-bishop's diagonal before Black plays ...f7-f5
himself.} (42. a3 f5 {offers Black chances to defend his fortress on the light
squares.}) 42... Ne5 43. Kd4 Bc6 44. Bf3 ({The immediate} 44. e4 {also wins,
but the last move is typical for the "Do not hurry - the opponent may make
things easier for you!" policy.}) 44... Bb7 ({The game went} 44... g5 $2 45.
fxg6 Be8 46. g7 Bf7 47. a3 {1-0 Andersson,U (2635)-Handoko,E (2420) Jakarta
1983}) 45. e4 $1 dxe4 46. Bxe4 Bc8 (46... Bxe4 47. Kxe4 {wins a pawn on e5
soon due to Zugzwang.}) 47. a3 {Putting Black in Zugzwang with a useful move,
defending b4.} Bd7 48. Bb7 Kc7 49. Bxa6 Kd6 (49... Kb6 50. Bxe5 fxe5+ 51. Kxe5
Kxa6 52. Kd6 $18 {Black's king is too passive to generate counterplay and the
f-pawn will promote soon.}) 50. Bb7 Be8 51. h4 Bd7 52. Be4 Be8 53. Bd5 Bd7 54.
h5 Be8 55. Ke4 Bd7 56. g5 $1 hxg5 57. Bxe5+ fxe5 58. f6 gxf6 59. h6 $18 *

