{[#]White's structural advantage is obvious, but with his last move Black
seems to have forced the transposition to an ending with opposite-colored
bishops, offering him reasonable drawing chances. Which is White's strongest
answer?} 43. Rd1 $1 {This does not really sacrifice a pawn, and if Black
exchanges the knights he will lose the d6-pawn.} (43. Nxe6 Bxe6 $14) 43... Ke7
$1 {The best defense.} (43... Nxd4 44. Rxd4 Bc6 45. Bxd6 $18 {Besides his
positional advantage, White also has an extra pawn, greatly diminishing the
drawing chances offered by the opposite-colored bishops.}) (43... Nxg5 $2 44.
Nxb5 Bc6 (44... axb5 45. Rxd5) (44... Bxb3 45. Nxd6+) 45. Nxd6+ $18 {Andersson,
U (2640)-Hracek,Z (2625) Berlin 1996 (1-0, 57)}) 44. Nxb5 Bxb3 45. Rh1 $3 {
A fantastic move, removing the rook from the attacked squares and keeping the
queenside tension intact while attacking h7.} axb5 (45... Nxg5 46. Nxd6 $18)
46. Rxh7+ Kd8 47. Rh8+ Kc7 48. axb3 Nxg5 49. Ba5+ Kc6 50. Rc8+ Kb7 51. Re8 Kc6
52. Bd2 Nf7 53. Re6 Ne5 54. Bb4 $16 {White's structural advantage is as
consistent as in the initial position, but there are no more opposite-colored
bishops on the board.} *

