{[#]Black has a dominant position and an extra pawn. Which is the most
convincing winning method?} 51... Bd8 $1 {This typical "Ulf retreat" prepares
to isolate the knight with ...Be7-d6. White's king cannot evacuate the h2-b8
diagonal in time in order to meet ...Be7 with Nc7.} (51... Bc5 {planning ...
Bd6 also wins, but some precise calculating is required.} 52. Nxc5 Kxc5 53. Ke5
Nc4+ 54. Kf6 Kxb5 55. Kxf7 g5 $1 (55... a5 $2 56. Kxg6 a4 57. Bd1 a3 58. Bb3
Nd2 59. Ba2 {, and it is Black who has to find a series of only moves to save
the game.} Ne4 60. Kxh6 Nc3 61. Be6 Kc5 62. Bb3 Kb4 63. Be6 Kc5 64. g5 Nd5 65.
Bxd5 Kxd5 66. g6 a2 67. g7 a1=Q 68. g8=Q+ Ke4 $11) 56. Kg7 a5 57. Kxh6 a4 58.
Bd1 a3 59. Bb3 Nd2 60. Ba2 Nf3 $19 {Comparing this line with Ulf's
continuation, we can understand that his choice was by far more practical as
White has no counterplay at all.}) 52. Bd1 Be7 53. Kg3 Bd6+ 54. Kg2 f5 {
White is playing with a piece less so he rightly decided to resign in Smejkal,
J (2550) -Andersson, U (2585) Reggio Emilia 1986} *

