{[#]Searching for a way to clear paths for his bishops' pair, Kortschnoj
offered the queen exchange. How should Black react?} 49... Qxa8 $1 {Black
cannot avoid the exchange anyway, so it is useful to force the bishop to the
most passive square on whole board.} (49... Qe8 $6 50. Qa7 $16 {would offer
White strong pressure.}) 50. Bxa8 Ba4 $1 {The activation of the bishop is the
highest priority, as its rival is temporarily out of play.} (50... Ng6 $6 51.
Kf2 Ba4 52. Ke2 $1 Bb3 53. Bc6 (53. Kd3 Nh4) 53... Bxc4+ 54. Ke3 Nf4 55. Ba4
$15 {offers White chances to hold due to his (now) well-coordinated bishops.})
51. Bc6 Bd1 52. Bd2 (52. Be1 Ng6 53. Kg2 Nh4+ 54. Bxh4 gxh4 55. Bb5 h3+ 56.
Kxh3 Bxf3 $19) 52... Ng6 $1 {The attack against f3 is decisive already.} 53.
Be3 Nh4 54. f4 exf4+ 55. Bxf4 gxf4+ 56. Kxh4 Bc2 57. Kh3 Bxe4 58. Ba4 Kf7 59.
Bd1 Bd3 {0-1 Kortschnoj,V (2600)-Andersson,U (2635) Wijk aan Zee 1983} 60. Bb3
Kg6 61. Kh4 Kh6 {White loses due to successive Zugzwang positions.} 62. Kh3 (
62. Ba2 Bc2) 62... Kg5 63. Ba2 Bc2 $19 *

