{[#]The structure is almost symmetrical, but the queenside situation is rather
tense. How do you evaluate the position and what would you play with Black?} 
29... e5 $1 {This is the strongest continuation, allowing Black to maintain
approximate equality. The main idea is that Black needs his bishop to take
part in the fight.} (29... Rb8 $6 30. Ra1 {23/581} Nb4 31. Bxb4 axb4 32. Ra7 b3
33. Ne1 e5 34. dxe5 Bxe5 35. Nd3 $14 {White retains some advantage due to his
active rook and the permanent weakness on b3.}) (29... Kf5 $2 {This is the
game continuation, obviously aiming to activate the king, which you are
invited to punish when solving the next test.}) 30. Ra1 Nb4 31. Bxb4 (31. Nxb4
axb4 32. Kc2 bxa3 33. Kxb3 axb2 34. Rd1 exd4 35. exd4 Bxd4 $1 {and Black is
not worse.}) 31... axb4 32. Rb1 exd4 33. exd4 (33. Na1 dxe3+ 34. Kc2 Rxb2+ 35.
Rxb2 Bxb2 36. Kxb2 exf2 $19) 33... Rf3 34. Ke2 g4 35. Ne1 Rf5 36. Rd1 Bg5 $11 *

