{[#]Black had been forced to sacrifice his queen earlier under unclear
circumstances. Pawns are equal now, yielding White a small overall material
advantage. The central and kingside structure also favor White, but Black has
some attacking chances due to the control over the d-file and the
effectiveness of his bishop, which is able to defend and attack at the same
time. There is only one move which allows White to maintain an advantage.} 37.
b3 $3 {This strong move prevents Black from creating the dangerous network
around the white king based on the blocking ...Bb3.} (37. e5 $6 {This was
played in the game but has the drawback of allowing Black to install the
bishop on b3, thus creating serious queenside threats.} Rd2 38. Qf3 R2d3 39.
Qg4 Bb3 $1 {After this typical move, threatening ...Rd1+ winning, White has to
release the pressure on g7 and think about his own defense.} (39... R3d4 40. f4
Bb3 {is also possible.}) ({But} 39... a5 $2 {allows the familiar idea} 40. b3
$1 Bxb3 41. f4 $18) 40. Rc1 Rd1 41. Kb1 {We have reached a position which you
will deal with in the next test.}) (37. b4 $6 {The idea behind this move is
the same as that of b2-b3, but weakening the third rank allows Black to
activate his more advanced rook with a gain of time.} Rd3 38. Qg4 Rxa3+ {
This is the difference, the rook can leave its colleague undefended.} 39. Kb1
Rb3+ 40. Kc2 Rbd3 41. e5 R3d4 42. f4 Rc4+ 43. Kb2 Rxb4+ {with a draw by
perpetual check, as} 44. Ka3 $2 {allows the other rook to join the attack with
decisive effect.} Rb3+ 45. Ka4 Rd4+) 37... Bxb3 ({Black is not in time to
create threats with his rook after} 37... Rd3 38. Qg4 {as the d7-rook is
hanging, and moving it away along the seventh rank would allow Rg3.}) 38. e5
Rd2 39. Qg4 {White threatens f2-f4 followed by e5-e6 and f4-f5 with a crushing
advantage. Black cannot create real threats with a rook and bishop, as the
white king has enough breathing space.} *

