{[#]White has managed to stop the first wave of Black's attack and the
position tends to be statically balanced. Andersson found a way to add spice
to the fight, which, even though it does not change the global evaluation,
offers practical chances. Can you find it, too?} 41... g5 $5 {There are two
main ideas behind this surprising move. If White leaves the structure
unchanged, the e5-pawn will be cut off his colleague on the f-file in the pawn
ending resulting after the probable exchange of all pieces. And if White takes
on g6, as he did in the game, the king will have free paths to the center
while the h-pawn will become a candidate to promotion.} (41... a5 $6 {Such
neutral moves allow White to retain some advantage with} 42. e6 R7d4 (42...
Rxc1+ $2 43. Kxc1 Rd1+ 44. Qxd1 Bxd1 45. Kxd1 Kg8 46. f4 $18) 43. Qf3 R4d3 44.
e7 Rxc1+ 45. Kxc1 Rxf3 46. e8=Q+ Bg8 47. Qa8 $14) (41... R7d4 42. Qc8+ Rd8 43.
Qg4 R8d4 44. Qf3 R4d3 $11) (41... Rxc1+ 42. Kxc1 Rd1+ 43. Qxd1 Bxd1 44. Kxd1 g5
{(apart from 44...g6 the only move which does not lose) is another possible
move order that transposes to the game.}) 42. hxg6 {The most logical answer.} (
42. Qe2 $2 Kg7 43. Qf3 Rxc1+ 44. Kxc1 Rd1+ 45. Qxd1 Bxd1 46. Kxd1 Kf7 47. Ke2
Ke6 48. Ke3 Kxe5 $19) (42. Qf3 $5 {threatening perpetual check is also enough
to maintain equality.} Rxc1+ 43. Kxc1 Rd1+ 44. Qxd1 Bxd1 45. Kxd1 Kg7 46. Ke2
Kf7 47. Ke3 Ke6 48. f4 $1 (48. Ke4 $2 g4 $1 49. Kf4 a5 {, and White is
helpless against the advance of the queenside majority, for instance:} 50. Kxg4
Kxe5 51. f4+ Ke4 52. f5 Ke5) 48... gxf4+ 49. Kxf4 a5 50. a4 b5 51. axb5 cxb5
52. Ke4 a4 53. Kd4 b4 54. Kc4 a3 55. bxa3 bxa3 56. Kb3 Kxe5 57. Kxa3 Kf5 58.
Kb3 Kg5 59. Kc3 Kxh5 60. Kd3 Kg4 61. Ke2 Kg3 62. Kf1 $11) (42. e6 $2 Rxc1+ 43.
Kxc1 Rd1+ 44. Qxd1 Bxd1 45. Kxd1 Kg7 $19) 42... Rxc1+ 43. Kxc1 Rd1+ 44. Qxd1
Bxd1 45. Kxd1 Kg7 46. f4 Kxg6 47. e6 Kf6 48. f5 {A very interesting pawn
ending. Black will soon have two passed pawns on the opposite wings, and the
only question remaining is whether White will be in time to create counterplay
with his pawns supported by the king.} a5 49. Ke2 {The king is heading for h6.}
({Even though less logical,} 49. Ke1 {is the other way of holding a draw.} a4
50. Kf2 b5 51. Kg3 c5 52. Kf3 b4 53. Ke4 c4 (53... bxa3 54. bxa3 c4 55. Kd4 h5
56. Kxc4 h4 57. Kd5 h3 58. Kd6 h2 59. e7 h1=Q 60. e8=Q $11) 54. axb4 c3 55. Kd3
cxb2 56. Kc2 h5 57. b5 h4 58. b6 b1=Q+ 59. Kxb1 h3 60. b7 h2 61. b8=Q h1=Q+ {
with a draw.}) 49... a4 50. Kf3 h5 (50... b5 51. Kg4 c5 {Transposes}) 51. Kg3
b5 52. Kh4 c5 53. Kxh5 b4 {We have reached a crucial moment in which White
finally went wrong. You are invited to do better by solving the next test.} *

