[FEN "8/1p5p/4k1p1/2p1P3/1P6/P4K2/7P/8 w - - 0 38"]
[PlyCount "19"]
[EventDate "2018.09.25"]
[Source "ChessBase"]

{[#]With his previous moves Andersson undermined White's center (36...c5 37.
bxc5 bxc5). Since White's passed pawn is central and Black has a mobile
outside kingside majority, accuracy is needed in order to hold a draw. Your
move.} 38. Kf4 $1 {It is essential to threaten Kg5 and provoke ...h7-h6. This
way, Black is forced to spend one of his reserve tempi earlier than he would
have liked to.} (38. Ke4 $2 {This natural but too "neutral" move allows Black
to keep all his reserve tempi, which will soon be the decisive element.} cxb4
$1 (38... c4 39. a4 c3 40. Kd3 Kxe5 41. Kxc3 g5 42. a5 $11) 39. axb4 g5 40. Kd4
(40. b5 h6 41. h3 b6 42. Kd4 h5 {With the white pawn on h3, the majority is
easier to convert into an outside passed pawn.} 43. Ke4 g4 44. hxg4 hxg4 45.
Kf4 g3 46. Kxg3 Kxe5 47. Kf3 Kd5 48. Ke3 Kc5 49. Kd3 Kxb5 50. Kc3 Ka4 $19)
40... h5 {0-1 Czerniak,M-Andersson,U Gothenburg 1971} 41. Ke4 b5 {Zugzwang!
The white king has to step further away from the kingside, allowing the pawns'
advance.} 42. Kd4 g4 43. Ke4 h4 44. Kf4 g3 45. hxg3 hxg3 46. Kxg3 Kxe5 47. Kf3
Kd4 48. Ke2 Kc4 49. Kd2 Kxb4 50. Kc2 Ka3 $19) (38. bxc5 $2 Kxe5 $19 {will soon
yield Black an extra pawn.}) 38... cxb4 (38... c4 39. a4 c3 40. Ke3 Kxe5 41.
Kd3 g5 42. a5 $11) 39. axb4 h6 (39... Kd5 40. Kg5 Kxe5 41. Kh6 $11) 40. Ke4 g5
{The same position was reached in the game, but with the h-pawn on its initial
square.} 41. b5 b6 42. Kd4 Ke7 $1 {Black already has to play the only move to
make a draw.} (42... h5 $2 43. Ke4 g4 44. Kf4 Ke7 45. Kg5 Ke6 46. Kxh5 Kxe5 47.
Kxg4 $18) 43. Kd5 Kd7 44. e6+ Ke7 45. Ke5 h5 46. Kf5 g4 47. Kg5 {This does not
win now, as the e6-pawn is on the enemy king's shortest way to f5. Black will
follow with 47...Kxe6 48.Kxh5 Kf5=} *

