{[#]Black has an extra pawn, but also two doubled pawns pairs. What really
makes his position promising is the more active king. There is only one move
for White which does not lose by force.} 44. g3 $1 {This is the best way to
fight for space and keep as many reserve tempi as possible. In the next test,
you are kindly invited to find the best practical chance for Black. 0-1 (10)
Planas Gene, J (2191)-Andersson, U (2542) Calvia 2006} (44. f4+ $2 {leads to a
series of Zugzwang positions soon.} Kd5 45. Kd3 Kc5 46. g3 Kd5 47. h4 Kc5 48.
Kc2 Kc4 {This is the most systematic continuation.} ({But Black can also take
advantage of the fact that he did not have to spend the reserve tempo ...b6-b5,
resulting in the essential detail that the second b-pawn requires an extra
tempo to be captured.} 48... Kd4 49. Kb3 Ke3 50. Kxb4 Kf3 51. Kb5 Kxg3 52. Kxb6
Kxf4 53. a4 Kg3 54. a5 f4 55. a6 f3 56. a7 f2 57. a8=Q f1=Q $19 {Black will
soon win the h4-pawn, when with two extra pawns he will have little trouble
winning, as his king will be safe.}) 49. Kb2 b5 50. Kc2 b3+ 51. axb3+ Kd4 52.
Kd2 b4 $19) (44. Kd3 $2 {allows Black a decisive gain of space:} f4 45. Kc4 Ke4
46. Kxb4 Kd3 47. Kb5 Ke2 48. f3 Kf2 49. Kxb6 Kxg2 50. a4 Kxf3 51. a5 Kg3 52. a6
f3 53. a7 f2 54. a8=Q f1=Q $19 {, with a familiar situation.}) (44. h4 $2 {
has the same drawback as 44.Kd3, even though concretely play may be slightly
different:} f4+ 45. Kf3 f5 46. Ke2 Ke4 47. Kd2 f3 48. g3 Kd4 $19) *

