[Source "ChessBase"]

{[#]White's position looks critical. Can he still save the game?} 48. Kc2 $1 {
was the correct move, retreating with the king as close to the b3-square as
possible, in order to be ready to start the queenside counterplay.} (48. f3 $2
{This was the decisive mistake. White spends this tempo too early.} Kd5 $1 49.
Kc2 Kc4 50. Kb2 b5 51. Kc2 b3+ $1 52. axb3+ Kd4 53. Kd2 b4 {0-1 Planas Gene,J 
(2191)-Andersson,U (2542) Calvia 2006}) (48. Kd2 $2 {takes the king too far
from b3, thus delaying White's counterplay.} Kd4 49. Kc2 (49. f3 b5 $19) 49...
Ke4 50. Kb3 Kxf4 51. Kxb4 Kg4 $1 (51... Kf3 52. Kb5 Kxf2 53. Kxb6 f4 54. a4 f3
55. a5 Kg3 56. a6 f2 57. a7 f1=Q 58. a8=Q $11 {Even though in practice White
is still in danger, the position is theoretical draw.}) 52. Kb5 Kxh4 53. Kxb6 {
That has been a long way indeed.} Kg5 54. a4 h4 55. a5 h3 56. a6 h2 57. a7 h1=Q
$19) 48... Kc4 (48... Kd4 49. Kb3 Ke4 50. Kxb4 Kxf4 51. Kb5 Kf3 52. Kxb6 Kxf2
53. a4 $11) 49. Kb2 b5 50. Kc2 b3+ {The same plan as in the game.} 51. axb3+
Kd4 52. Kd2 Ke4 (52... b4 {does not win because White still has} 53. f3 $11 {
in reserve.}) 53. Kc3 Kxf4 54. Kb4 Kf3 55. Kxb5 f4 56. Kc5 Kxf2 57. b4 Kg2 58.
b5 f3 59. b6 f2 60. b7 f1=Q 61. b8=Q $11 {Once again the endgame is
theoretically drawn, but over the board Black still has chances.} *

